\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1}{\ignorespaces Generational convergence of the genetic algorithm across the target-directivity campaign. The curves show that most of the objective reduction occurs early in the search, but final target errors remain finite and target-dependent. The figure should be interpreted as evidence of model-level target-shape adaptation, not as proof of absolute noise reduction.}}{11}{figure.1}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:campaign_mse}{{1}{11}{Generational convergence of the genetic algorithm across the target-directivity campaign. The curves show that most of the objective reduction occurs early in the search, but final target errors remain finite and target-dependent. The figure should be interpreted as evidence of model-level target-shape adaptation, not as proof of absolute noise reduction}{figure.1}{}}
\@writefile{lot}{\contentsline {table}{\numberline {1}{\ignorespaces Campaign performance across the 50-target set. Values are means across targets, with standard deviations shown for acoustic RMSE and RMSE improvement. Drag ratio and lift-to-drag retention are low-order aerodynamic proxies, not validated aerodynamic coefficients.}}{11}{table.1}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{tab:campaign_results}{{1}{11}{Campaign performance across the 50-target set. Values are means across targets, with standard deviations shown for acoustic RMSE and RMSE improvement. Drag ratio and lift-to-drag retention are low-order aerodynamic proxies, not validated aerodynamic coefficients}{table.1}{}}
\@writefile{lot}{\contentsline {table}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces Performance variation by target lobe class for the full-geometry optimization. The values demonstrate that higher complexity targets (three lobes) tend to yield larger relative noise improvements, though absolute final errors remain dependent on baseline mismatch.}}{12}{table.2}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{tab:lobe_results}{{2}{12}{Performance variation by target lobe class for the full-geometry optimization. The values demonstrate that higher complexity targets (three lobes) tend to yield larger relative noise improvements, though absolute final errors remain dependent on baseline mismatch}{table.2}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces Selected optimized directivity patterns against target shapes. The examples illustrate model-level redistribution of normalized directivity, but the residual mismatch remains visible for difficult targets. The campaign should therefore be described as target-shape improvement rather than exact target synthesis.}}{12}{figure.2}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:campaign_directivity}{{2}{12}{Selected optimized directivity patterns against target shapes. The examples illustrate model-level redistribution of normalized directivity, but the residual mismatch remains visible for difficult targets. The campaign should therefore be described as target-shape improvement rather than exact target synthesis}{figure.2}{}}
